   "hider_text": "The air in the corner is thick with the smell of old wood and dust that doesn’t settle — it *sifts*. It moves like breath in a room that’s never quite warm enough. There’s a groove in the wall, just below the ceiling where the plaster has cracked and curled inward, like skin pulled too tight. You can feel it when you press your palm against it — not / The wind hums through the hollows of the old oak behind the bakery—dry leaves skittering like tiny fingers. It brushes the iron railing where the morning frost still clings, thin and silver, like breath on glass.  \n\nThere’s a gap in the stone wall near the back gate. Not big enough for a person, but just wide enough for a shadow to stretch across the pattern / The wind carries dust like breath between stones. It doesn’t blow— it *moves*, a slow exhale across flat ground, lifting fine white powder that settles in hollows and creases of ancient rock. The sun is not light, it is pressure, pressing down through a sky so wide it has no edges.  \n\nThere are places where the earth cracks like old leather— not from heat,",
